<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-677-889  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 677 889.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 4 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft increases Natural Language stake.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Investment activities)Natural Language Inc. (Securities).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Topic:     Securities TransferSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MICROSOFT INCREASES NATURAL LANGUAGE STAKE 12/04/90 BELLEVUE, WASHINGTON,U.S.A., 1990 DEC 4 (NB) -- Microsoft has increased its equity in NaturalLanguage Inc., of San Francisco, and indicated it plans to use the company'stechnology in future systems software.andP;  Natural Language develops softwarewhich lets computer users get at data using plain-English commands.andM;By investing an additional US$1 million, Microsoft has increased its share inthe six-year-old company to 10 percent.andP;  Other backers of Natural Languageinclude an assortment of venture capital firms and Stanford University.andM;Brenda Hansen, a spokeswoman for Microsoft, said the company expects to usethe natural language technology in systems products, primarily Windows andOS/2.andP;  Microsoft sees natural language as complementary to the graphicalinterfaces used in those products, she said.andP;  &quot;Graphics won't do it alone.&quot;andM;In a prepared statement, Microsoft Chairman William Gates called naturallanguage technology &quot;an important part of providing information at yourfingertips,&quot; referring to the title of his recent Comdex keynote speech and aposition paper released by Microsoft in November.andM;Although Microsoft has had an agreement with Natural Language since 1987giving it the right to use the company's technology, it has not incorporatedthe technology in any commercial products yet, Hansen said.andP;  Nor are productsthat use it imminent.andP;  &quot;We haven't released any timetable,&quot; she said, but sheindicated it would take some time for natural-language products to appear.andM;Natural Language uses the technology in software tools designed to provideaccess to databases, but Microsoft's applications would not necessarily bedatabase-related, Hansen said.andM;(Grant Buckler/19901204/Press Contact: Marty Taucher or Brenda Hansen,Microsoft, 206-882-8080; Mary Bilz, Blanc andamp; Otus Public Relations for NaturalLanguage, 415-546-8080; Amy Romanoff, Natural Language, 415-841-3500)</TEXT></DOC>